^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk about the bidding. First of all, particularly since it went P-P-weak 2. Sandy's hand is so good the only question is which major game to play in. Her best bid is 3D—Michaels intending to raise whichever suit Stan bids to 4. Sandy got a bit lucky here.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Ann violated the LOTT by bidding 3D. Had she passed, then Stan would have passed and they end up in 2S.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Michaels is a) both majors over a minor or b) the other major and an unspecified minor over a major. So 2D-3D Michaels is both majors. 1H-2H Michaels is spades and an unknown minor. Some experts play 2H-3H a different way, but every expert plays 2D-3D as Michaels.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|1H-2H is spades and either diamonds or clubs. I suggest you play 2H-3H as Michaels as well just to keep things consistent. However, FYI, some experts play that asks partner to bid 3N with a heart stopper. The type of hand where you would do that is if it goes 2H or 2S and you have a hand with a long running minor where you can see 9 tricks if pard has a stopper. However, as I said, to keep it simple, since the expert use rarely comes up, I suggest you play it as Michaels.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


nt|^B@2
Y2bridge:  Even after a weak-2 bid-2D?|
